[2
Date: Wed 28 Feb 2001 11:29:34 +0100
From: Wolfgang Preiser <W.Preiser@em.uni-frankfurt.de>

Another Correction
------------------
Regarding the posting entitled, Undiagnosed encephalitis - Malaysia
20010226.0381, I would like to comment on Moderator CP's comment (".... It
is implied that the victim may have been exposed to Nipah virus during the
1998 outbreak. If this is correct, it suggests that immunity to Nipah virus
may be short-lived. There is no evidence that Nipah virus can initiate a
persistent infection....")
However, [on the contrary there is good evidence that exactly this may be
the case with the closely related Hendra virus. O'Sullivan JD, Allworth AM,
Paterson DL, et al., Fatal encephalitis due to novel paramyxovirus
transmitted from horses (Lancet 1997;349:93-5), describe a patient who died
of encephalitis 13 months after his initial infection with Hendra virus.
Furthermore, neurological relapse has also been reported in Nipah virus
infection - see Goh et al.: Clinical features of Nipah virus encephalitis
among pig farmers in Malaysia (NEJM 342 (17): 1229-35).
--
Dr. med. Wolfgang Preiser, DTM&H, MRCPath
Institut f. Medizinische Virologie /
Reisemedizinische Impfambulanz
