[3
Date: Tue 27 Feb 2001 22:39:05 +0800
From: Dr. Muruga Vadivale <vale@pop.jaring.my>
Source: New Straits Times Press Report, Tue 27 Feb 2001 [edited
<http://www.emedia.com.my/Current_News/NST/Tuesday/NewsBreak/20010227152637>

Difficulties Experienced in the Follow-up of Nipah Virus Cases
--------------------------------------------------------------
A relapse of symptoms of Japanese Encephalitis (JE) virus/Nipah virus
infection have caused 2 deaths so far in the Bukit Pelandok area this year.
More deaths are expected if former victims do not seek follow-up treatment.
The Health Ministry has warned that former JE/Nipah victims may suffer a
relapse if they do not complete the 2-year schedule of follow-up treatment.
Its director-general, Datuk Dr. Mohamad Taha Arif, said that while there
were no new cases, 6 per cent of 280 people infected during the outbreak in
1999 had [experienced a relapse. "There is still that possibility
especially if they do not come for their follow-up [examination, but I
hope there would be no more," he told a press conference.
Dr. Mohamad Taha was concerned that of 78 patients who had turned up for
their first follow-up in July last year, only 52 returned for their second
check up, which eventually dwindled to only 20 for the third. "Efforts were
and are still being made to trace these patients. Some had moved away while
others were foreigners who may have returned home. The Ministry is
appealing to all patients to stick to their follow-up schedule and not to
drop out without completing it," he said.
Nipah virus [is a novel paramyxovirus resembling Hendra virus discovered
in Kampung Sungai Nipah, Bukit Pelanduk, during the height of the outbreak
in 1999. Dr. Mohamad Taha said health officials were also monitoring the
situation and conducting regular checks on areas that had been affected by
the outbreak. Since the Nipah virus outbreak in 1999, there had been 2
deaths reported in the media and both involved relapse cases. One was a
22-year old livestock farm assistant who died on 1 Feb 2001, and the other
was a former pig-farmer who died on 7 Feb 2001. Both were from the Bukit
Pelanduk pig-farming area near Lukut in Negri Sembilan.
The former pig farmer was a known case of Nipah encephalitis and he was
first admitted to Hospital in Kuala Lumpur on 16 Mar 1999 and displayed
residual neurological deficit on discharge. On subsequent reviews his
condition was found to have worsened and [it is presumed that he died at
home later. As for the 22-year old assistant, Dr Mohamad Taha said
investigations had revealed that he was involved in an unsupervised private
culling operation in early March 1999. This was when it was established
that the pigs were already infected with Nipah virus. It is highly probable
that he was infected during this time and subsequently he developed
prodromal symptoms in April 1999.
Dr. Mohamad Taha said initial blood tests taken from this patient after he
was admitted to the Seremban hospital on 28 Jan 2001 revealed he had
previous exposure to Nipah virus. He said health authorities were also
trying to verify the [nature of the illness suffered by the victim's
employer. We are trying to get his employer's private physician here (Kuala
Lumpur), to investigate further on how and when e he has been infected.
KL Hospital Consultant Neurologist Dr. Raihanah Abdul Khalid, who was also
present at the press conference, said follow-ups were done monthly for the
first 4 months, followed by [examinations at the sixth, ninth and twelfth
months. She said reminder letters [had been sent out to those who did not
turn up for any of the checks-ups, but so far these had been ineffective.
Dr. Raihanah said the Ministry had also extended the follow-up period
indefinitely from 2 years to learn more about the virus, [and especially to
determine if it exhibited cyclic activity.
"It is not unusual for some viruses," she said, "to linger on for a long
time even though the primary initial infection appears to have cleared up."
Mutations or some remnants of the virus can still remain and cause problems
later, she said. Dr. Raihanah said of the 280 patients infected during the
outbreak, 120 had died and of the remaining 160 patients, 126 tested Nipah
virus-positive while the rest could not be traced.
[Byline: Nelson Fernandez
--
Dr. Muruga Vadivale
