[4
Date: Tue 27 Feb 2001 18:06:07 -0500
From: Patricia Doyle, PhD <dr_p_doyle@hotmail.com>
Source: New Straits Times Press, Wed 28 Feb 2001 [edited
<http://www.nstpi.com.my/z/Current_News/NST/Tuesday/National/20010227083239>

Japanese Encephalitis Virus Suspected as Cause of Death
--------------------------------------------------------
SEREMBAN: Initial investigations into the death of a livestock farm
assistant at Bukit Pelandok on 29 Jan 2001 have ruled out Nipah virus as
the cause of death and indicate Japanese encephalitis was responsible.
[However, the Health and Veterinary Services Departments are running
further tests on blood samples taken from goats at the farm where the
22-year old man had been working. Veterinary Services Department
Director-general Datuk Dr. Mohd Nordin Mohd Noor said the tests were still
inconclusive as the investigators would also need to re-affirm that the
death was not Nipah virus-related. "We do not know everything about Nipah
virus, which has been known to be carried by pigs, so we will have to look
into every possibility. For now, we can ascertain from initial findings on
the victim's death that it was not Nipah virus-related, based on our
knowledge of the virus." Asked if it was necessary to evacuate the farm's
occupants and nearby residents, Dr. Mohd Nordin said the Health Department
would ascertain the social considerations in the case following the
conclusion of its tests. He said the investigators also could not confirm
whether the victim's death was caused by the residual effects of the Nipah
virus [infection contracted by him during the Nipah outbreak at Bukit
Pelandok in 1999.
He said that livestock farmers and villagers who came across Japanese
encephalitis-like sicknesses among their livestock or people should
immediately report to the relevant authorities. He added that he had
instructed the State Veterinary Services Department to carry out
investigations at the farm and the surrounding area to determine if there
is really a cause for concern.
Meanwhile, the owner of the affected farm said officers from the department
came at 8.30 a.m. today to collect blood samples from his goats. Meanwhile,
2 experts from the Department of Medicine, Universiti Malaya, came to Bukit
Pelandok to trace former Japanese encephalitis victims who failed to
undergo follow-up checks at government hospitals. This followed the death
of a Japanese encephalitis victim, whose identity was not available, at
Bukit Pelandok last week. One of the experts, Prof. C.T. Tan, said it was
possible for people exposed to Nipah virus to suffer from residual effects.
[Byline: R. Sittamparam
--
Patricia A. Doyle, PhD
<dr_p_doyle@hotmail.com>
